00:43:45.050 --> 00:43:46.540
Thank you so much, Meg.

00:43:46.540 --> 00:43:48.930
That was super informative.

00:43:48.930 --> 00:43:51.490
I've been working with
alt text for a long time

00:43:51.490 --> 00:43:52.930
but I learned a few things there.

00:43:54.640 --> 00:43:57.480
We had a question, and then you
actually touched on it there

00:43:57.480 --> 00:43:59.530
in that final slide.

00:44:01.190 --> 00:44:04.020
Maybe just to
reiterate the question.

00:44:04.020 --> 00:44:07.540
Is there an appropriate way to
write alt text for a person's image?

00:44:08.860 --> 00:44:12.430
Then asking the same question
whether it's a stock image

00:44:12.430 --> 00:44:14.970
or an actual photo
of someone you know.

00:44:16.810 --> 00:44:18.760
The person asking the question
says, "I don't want

00:44:18.760 --> 00:44:21.780
to misrepresent that
person or get it wrong."

00:44:21.780 --> 00:44:23.961
Any notes around that?

00:44:24.410 --> 00:44:27.260
>> MEG: There is not a
100% answer for this.

00:44:27.260 --> 00:44:29.330
Actually, the last time
I gave this presentation,

00:44:29.330 --> 00:44:30.850
somebody asked that
exact same thing.

00:44:33.450 --> 00:44:39.980
It's always different, and it
always depends on the writers.

00:44:39.980 --> 00:44:41.490
Like headshots at a company.

00:44:41.490 --> 00:44:43.900
Obviously you don't-- I
have that same yeti mug.

00:44:43.900 --> 00:44:48.740
At the same time you don't want
to have this the name repeated,

00:44:48.740 --> 00:44:51.760
because that's not
helpful, so what do you do?

00:44:51.760 --> 00:44:56.200
It is so hard to answer.

00:44:57.420 --> 00:45:00.330
For stock images, those people
know what they're getting into.

00:45:00.330 --> 00:45:05.700
You can describe them whatever
is important to what's going on.

00:45:07.380 --> 00:45:12.220
What I like to
recommend to people is

00:45:12.220 --> 00:45:15.300
if there is something like
a headshot being uploaded is

00:45:15.300 --> 00:45:18.750
to actually ask your employees
to provide their alt text.

00:45:20.030 --> 00:45:23.800
That would be my best
recommendation, because that struggle

00:45:23.800 --> 00:45:25.660
to misrepresent somebody is real.

00:45:27.280 --> 00:45:31.220
When it comes to people you
actually know, my best advice is

00:45:31.220 --> 00:45:33.430
to ask them how they
want to be described.

00:45:33.430 --> 00:45:38.450
If you're describing stock
images, general descriptions,

00:45:38.450 --> 00:45:40.270
whatever is important
about the image.

00:45:40.270 --> 00:45:45.930
I hope that helps.

00:45:45.930 --> 00:45:48.190
I'm sorry I can't
give you 100% answer

00:45:48.190 --> 00:45:51.470
because this is just not
a question that has one.

00:45:51.470 --> 00:45:52.390
>> CARRIE: Really helpful.

00:45:52.390 --> 00:45:53.570
Thank you.

00:45:53.570 --> 00:45:56.320
We've got about five minutes
here, so see

00:45:56.320 --> 00:45:58.520
if I can get some
quick questions to you.

00:45:59.560 --> 00:46:03.370
Does the screen reader also read
the caption or only the alt text?

00:46:03.370 --> 00:46:05.310
>> MEG: It will read the caption.

00:46:05.310 --> 00:46:07.140
That's why you don't
want to have alt text

00:46:07.140 --> 00:46:10.280
and the caption be the same thing
because then it just says it twice.

00:46:12.390 --> 00:46:16.170
It's one thing if they're
different, but just try not

00:46:16.170 --> 00:46:17.170
to make them duplicate.

00:46:17.850 --> 00:46:18.720
>> CARRIE: Got you.

00:46:20.080 --> 00:46:24.420
How do you approach training
content creators on this process?

00:46:24.420 --> 00:46:28.120
It can be complicated to make
decisions but as you say best not

00:46:28.120 --> 00:46:29.790
to overthink it.

00:46:29.790 --> 00:46:33.000
How would you bridge that
contradiction and training?

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:35.460
>> MEG: When you find out
how to train content creators

00:46:35.460 --> 00:46:37.380
to implement alt text, tell me.

00:46:40.350 --> 00:46:44.510
You will get better at alt text
every single time you do it.

00:46:44.510 --> 00:46:47.000
If you scroll back far enough in
my Twitter, I don't have alt text

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:51.240
on a lot of my images because it
just wasn't the practice I was in,

00:46:51.240 --> 00:46:54.240
but I started doing it and
then you get better at it.

00:46:54.240 --> 00:46:56.270
You start putting
your own twist on it.

00:46:56.270 --> 00:46:57.740
It's okay to be funny.

00:46:57.740 --> 00:47:00.540
Like I said in my slide,
you can be funny in your alt text

00:47:00.540 --> 00:47:03.360
and really express who you are
as the writer in your alt text.

00:47:07.720 --> 00:47:09.420
It's just getting them to start.

00:47:09.420 --> 00:47:12.250
That is the thing.

00:47:12.250 --> 00:47:15.590
As they practice, they start
getting more comfortable with it.

00:47:15.590 --> 00:47:15.990
"You know what?

00:47:15.990 --> 00:47:17.150
I can start adding this.

00:47:17.150 --> 00:47:18.580
I can start adding that.

00:47:18.580 --> 00:47:21.040
I think this would be a good
description for this image.

00:47:21.040 --> 00:47:25.340
How would I imagine this image if
I were having somebody describe it

00:47:25.340 --> 00:47:26.200
to me?"

00:47:26.200 --> 00:47:28.400
Those are the practices
people start thinking of

00:47:28.400 --> 00:47:31.920
as they start doing alt text more.

00:47:32.457 --> 00:47:33.305
>> CARRIE: That's fantastic.

00:47:34.280 --> 00:47:36.250
One last question for you.

00:47:36.250 --> 00:47:40.420
Going back to an e-commerce
store, if the alt text is the same

00:47:40.420 --> 00:47:45.360
as the product title, then screen
readers read the product name twice.

00:47:45.360 --> 00:47:48.410
Is that laziness or
is that acceptable?

00:47:51.160 --> 00:47:58.170
>> MEG: That would depend on if
your entire product title describe

00:47:58.170 --> 00:48:02.510
the image because
the whole [inaudible]

00:48:07.850 --> 00:48:13.240
if you just have an orange
couch in your product title,

00:48:13.240 --> 00:48:15.600
that isn't describing
the image properly.

00:48:17.520 --> 00:48:21.330
Actually that slide is
birthed out of this question

00:48:21.330 --> 00:48:23.450
that happened the
last time I gave this,

00:48:23.450 --> 00:48:25.570
except last time it was blue couch.

00:48:25.570 --> 00:48:27.100
Those details need to be told.

00:48:27.100 --> 00:48:29.210
You're not going to say
the gap between the couch

00:48:29.210 --> 00:48:30.280
and the product description.

00:48:30.280 --> 00:48:32.700
I've never seen something
like that before anyway.

00:48:32.700 --> 00:48:36.090
That's the kind of stuff that
needs to go into the alt text.

00:48:36.090 --> 00:48:38.510
They already know what
the product is called.

00:48:39.740 --> 00:48:41.490
Alt text is for describing
what it looks like.

